The so-called special verbs that govern the dative take this construction, not because of any arbitrary rule, but because from the Latin point of view they are intransitive and take an indirect object. The English meaning is not a sate guide‚ for it sometimes happens that two Latin verbs with the same English equivalence will be the one transitive, governing the accusative, and the other intransitive, governing the dative. For example, the Latin has the two verbs nocere and laedere, both translated to injure,· but the former is intransitive and the latter transitive.
